nodes.bodyText:
This method is called when the visitor does not handle a given type of data storage, so that it can fallback to a generic task if needed. I still prefer otherwise() to defaultVisit() because basically when this method is called, it means that you are not visiting any data storage. I used it for example like this:
    return otherBuffer.accept(new DataStorageVisitor<Boolean>() {

      @Override
      public Boolean visit(DoubleBuffer otherStorage) {
        return myStorage.equals(otherStorage);
      }

      @Override
      public Boolean otherwise() {
        for (int idx = 0; idx < size(); ++idx) {
          if (otherBuffer.getDouble(idx) != getDouble(idx)) {
            return false;
          }
        }
        return true;
      }
    });
So when otherwise() is call, I can only build a routine using the public API of a DataBuffer and nothing internal like other visit() methods can do.

